1. Problem Framing¶

The project that we are working on focuses on the dataset regarding the reviews of amazon purchases over almost two decades. In this complete dataset with over two million rows, it has a complete overview of customers’ reviews of their purchases on Amazon from as early as 1995 until 2015. It’s rather interesting to have a peek upon the general feedback people have been having with the products they acquire on the largest e-commerce platform. In a way, we’d like to explore what people feel about their purchase experience and if Amazon has done a good job in providing people the product they are looking for. To be specific, we are investigating the dataset under the genre of grocery shopping. We want to look into grocery because it’s an everyday necessity. It includes leisure snacks as well as daily consuming meals. A particular reason that grocery sparks our interest is the pandemic situation that we are under currently.

Considering the current COV19 pandemic situation, many of us are staying self-quarantined and basically stuck at home. Even the most ordinary trip to a supermarket like Publix or Kroger may feel like a risk. The demand of online grocery shopping has peaked ever since the pandemic. From our personal experience, Amazon Fresh, the service to deliver grocery daily has been greatly demanded and spared no effort to keep up the popular need. Other services like Instacart or Costco Membership delivery have all been compromised somewhat due to the virus outbreak. The online grocery is what many of us rely on to survive even, we are counting on it to deliver poultry, vegetable, and well some ice-creams to enjoy. We want to see if Amazon has been doing a great job and the general pattern of people’s comments, so that it may serve helpful for people already doing Amazon shopping to decide what to buy under this particular situation or a first-timer joining Amazon to convince them it’s a rather good choice for their daily needs right now.

Online grocery has become one of the most popular ways of purchasing grocery nowadays, especially for the current pandemic situation. Many e-commerce platforms have started their competitions in order to attract more customers, and two of dominant platforms are Amazon fresh and Instacart, and here is a video to compare the pros and cons of these two platforms. From the video and related materials, we can easily find that in addition to shipment efficiency, grocery diversity, as well as quality, one thing that affect customers a lot.

2.1.2 Data Collection: Create S3 Bucket¶

We create an S3 bucket that will be used throughout the workshop for storing data.

def create_bucket(bucket):
    import logging

    try:
        s3.create_bucket(Bucket=bucket, CreateBucketConfiguration={'LocationConstraint': region})
    except botocore.exceptions.ClientError as e:
        logging.error(e)
        return 'Bucket {0} could not be created.'.format(bucket)
    return 'Created {0} bucket.'.format(bucket)
create_bucket(bucket)

2.3 Feature Engineering¶

2.3.1 Feature Engineering: Add New Column sentiment Based on star_rating¶

We use apply method to apply a function to each row in the DataFrame by adding a new column sentiment. This will make it easier to visualize the data later.

def get_sentiment(value):
    if value > 3:
        return "positive"
    else:
        return "negative"
df['sentiment'] = df['star_rating'].apply(get_sentiment)
df.head()

3. Data Visualization & Analysis¶

3.1 Domain Knowledge and Data Schema¶

3.1.1 Domain Knowledge and Data Schema: Domain Knowledge¶

(1) Word cloud is a visual representation of text data, typically used to depict keyword metadata (tags) on websites, or to visualize free form text. In word cloud representations the most frequent words in a document are graphically represented with larger sizes. With the help of word cloud, we could visualize our data and find the high-frequency words in the document.

(2) In this dataset, we use the "star_rating" column to reflect people's satisfaction, which has a scale of 1-5, with 1 as the lowest, 3 as neutral, and 5 has highest satisfaction level

3.1.2 Domain Knowledge and Data Schema: Data Schema¶

Part 1:

As we have already done in the data preparation process, we convert the star rating into two opposite groups in a new factor variable “sentiment”. We consider the rating of 1 star and 2 stars as negative comments while the rating of 4 stars and 5 stars as positive comments.

Here are all the variables we are dealing with in the whole dataset.

  • Review_body (string): shows the content of the review for a certain product.
  • Star_rating (factor): shows how much the customer likes a certain product.
  • Sentiment (factor): shows the sentiment inclination based on the star rating results.

Part 2:

Later, since we need to conduct a deeper analysis of the data, we add more quantitative criteria (numeric variables) based on the content of the review body. This modification will contribute to the correlation test and regression analysis.

Here are all the other variables we are dealing with in the dataset besides the three above.

  • Num_words (number): shows how many words there are in the review body part.
  • Num_unique_words (number): shows how many unique words there are in the review body part.
  • Num_chars (number): shows how many characters there are in the review body part.
  • Num_stopwords (number): shows how many stopwords (i.e. “the”, “a/an”, “in”) there are in the review body part.
  • Num_punctuations (number): shows how many punctuations there are in the review body part.
  • Mean_word_len (number): shows the average length of the words in the review body part.

Since we would like to see what words stand out in the dataset, we use WordCloud visualization to accomplish goal.

First, we use pip t oinstall the library.

from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS

Second, we build a simple function plot_wordcloud to plot the words.

def plot_wordcloud(text, mask=None, max_words=150, max_font_size=150, figure_size=(25.0,15.0), 
                   title = None, title_size=40, image_color=False):
    stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)

    wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color='black',
                    stopwords = stopwords,
                    max_words = max_words,
                    max_font_size = max_font_size, 
                    random_state = 50,
                    width=800, 
                    height=400,
                    mask = mask)
    wordcloud.generate(str(text))

    plt.figure(figsize=figure_size)
    if image_color:
        image_colors = ImageColorGenerator(mask);
        plt.imshow(wordcloud.recolor(color_func=image_colors), interpolation="bilinear");
        plt.title(title, fontdict={'size': title_size,  
                                  'verticalalignment': 'bottom'})
    else:
        plt.imshow(wordcloud);
        plt.title(title, fontdict={'size': title_size, 'color': 'red', 
                                  'verticalalignment': 'bottom'})
    plt.axis('off');
    plt.tight_layout()  

plot_wordcloud(df['review_body'], title="Word Cloud Review_Comments of Amazon Reviews")

3.3 Data Analysis¶

3.3.1 Data Analysis: Summary Statistics of review_body¶

First, We use string package to explore more about review_body. We calculate the number of words in the text, the number of unique words in the text, the number of characters in the text, the number of stopwords in the text, the number of punctuations in the text, and the average length of the words in the text.

import string

## Number of words in the text ##
df["num_words"] = df["review_body"].apply(lambda x: len(str(x).split()))

## Number of unique words in the text ##
df["num_unique_words"] = df["review_body"].apply(lambda x: len(set(str(x).split())))

## Number of characters in the text ##
df["num_chars"] = df["review_body"].apply(lambda x: len(str(x)))

## Number of stopwords in the text ##
df["num_stopwords"] = df["review_body"].apply(lambda x: len([w for w in str(x).lower().split() if w in STOPWORDS]))

## Number of punctuations in the text ##
df["num_punctuations"] = df['review_body'].apply(lambda x: len([c for c in str(x) if c in string.punctuation]) )

## Average length of the words in the text ##
df["mean_word_len"] = df["review_body"].apply(lambda x: np.mean([len(w) for w in str(x).split()]))

Second, we use describe function to show the summary of statistics of those variables.

df.describe()

3.3.2 Data Analysis: Correlation between star_rating and num_word¶

We would like to explore that whether the rating reviews that have more number of words will result in a negative star rating outcome. But surprisingly, we only find that the correlation coefficient is -0.0856. (Since we believe longer review comments tend to be more negative, since those customers have more to complain about)

print("Correlation of star_rating and num_words: {}".format(df.star_rating.corr(df.num_words)))

3.3.3 Data Analysis: Simple Regression Model of star_rating and num_word¶

Although there is only a weak correlation between the star rating and number of word, we still would like to explore whether there is a linear relationship. But the result shows a correspondence with the result of correlation coefficient: they do not have a strong linear relationship since the adjusted R-square is only 0.007, which is too low to reflect a strong linear relationship between star_rating and num_word

import statsmodels.api as sm
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

# print the summary of the results
results = smf.ols('star_rating ~ num_words', data=df).fit()
print(results.summary())

4.3 Improve the Process by Automatic Updates with Lambda¶

4.3.1 What are lambda functions?¶

AWS Lambda is a serverless compute service that lets you run code without provisioning or managing servers. AWS Lambda executes your code only when needed and scales automatically, from a few requests per day to thousands per second.

There are 3 types of methods by which you can deploy your code on AWS Lambda.

  • Using in-line editor and working with libraries only available in Lambda. (up to 3 MB)
  • Making a zipped deployment package and uploading it via Lambda console. (up to 50 MB)
  • Making a zipped package and saving it in the S3 bucket. (up to 250 MB when unzipped)

4.3.2 Why are we doing automatic updates with lambda?¶

If we make the Lambda function using a zip file present on S3, the code is not updated if we make any changes in the zip file. For the Lambda to get updated, we have to go to the console and update it manually.

4.3.3 How are we going to achieve this?¶

We will be using AWS Developer Tools and an intermediate Lambda function.

  • Create S3 Bucket — Create an S3 bucket that will store your zip file for lambda.
  • Create Lambda Functions — Create 2 lambdas. The main function ( say targetLambda) can be created using your desired environment and the intermediate one (say intermediateLambda) we will create using NodeJs environment. Let the targetLambda be empty for now. The intermediateLambda’s code would look like the following:

Lets now add an S3 trigger to intermediateLambda so that whenever there is any change in zip file present in the bucket this function is called.

  • Create CodeBuild — The first step is to tell CodeBuild which repo and branch to use to create the zip file and make a Buildspec file. We will edit the Buildspec file in the console and make changes in build and artifacts. Run this step and ensure that your zipped file is pushed to your desired destination in the S3.

5. Domain-Specific Goal Evaluation & Prediction¶

5.1 Evaluation¶

As we mentioned in our problem framing, buying groceries on e-commerce platforms like Amazon fresh is getting to be increasingly popular, and due to the corona virus outbreak, we believe it will still last for at least a couple of months, and it motivates us to evaluate the data and information on customer reviews on grocery section of Amazon. As we predicted, customer reviews play a significant role in the online grocery market, and we would like to analyze data that we have to investigate whether our prediction is right.

First, we would like to visualize the review counts in different classifications: we first draw the histograms related to the number of reviews with different ratings, from 1 to 5(highest), and we can find tht 5 star reviews are much more than other stars reviews, which indicates that the majority customers are satisfied with their orders. In addition to the ratings, we also visualize the sentiment of reviews by classifying reviews in two categories: positive and negative. Not surprisingly, the number of positive sentiment reviews reaches 1,802,648, and it is 6 times more than negative reviews (270,754). From these results, we can simply find the satisfying rate on average is about 87%, which is higher than we thought initially.

Moreover, we use WordCloud to visualize the keywords in customer reviews, and show them together in one picture and present them the size according to their appearance frequency, and from the result, we can surprisingly find that magazine is the most frequent word in the review, along with, love, best, great, time, and so on. We can find positive words are dominant, so that we can also find that positive reviews are more than negative reviews.

Since our initial conclusion is that positive reviews are far more than negative reviews, we then would like to see what is related to review ratings from our dataset. Our first thought is to correlate star-rating with the number of words in one review because we have heard that positive reviews tend to be more concise. Then we run the simple regression model of star_rating and num_word. Unfortunately, the R-squared of the model is only 0.007, which implies there is no correlation between two variables, and our hypothesis is not correct.

Even though we only apply our analysis in the grocery section of Amazon reviews, we can in fact apply it into different categories in different sections, and since ols regression model is one of the most popular analysis tools currently, we can in fact run ols regression model with any two numeric variables. Therefore, we believe our analysis has a wide-range of applications.

6.2 Image Label¶

First step in this kind of analytics is to recognize that we are actually looking at an image which may represent a grocery store). We create image_labels function which uses detect_lables Rekognition API to detect objects within an image. The function prints labels detected with confidence score.

In the given example notice somewhere in the middle of the labels listing at certain percentage confidence the Rekognition computer vision model should have determined a grocery store.

def image_labels(bucket, key):
    image_object = {'S3Object':{'Bucket': bucket,'Name': key}}

    response = rekognition.detect_labels(Image=image_object)
    for label in response['Labels']:
        print('{} ({:.0f}%)'.format(label['Name'], label['Confidence']))
image_labels(image_bucket, 'grocery.png')
